1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,680
In this video, we will talk about transformer architecture,

2

00:00:04,680  -->  00:00:09,715
which is the core innovation behind the Generative AI boom.

3

00:00:09,715  -->  00:00:12,980
It allows [inaudible] models to process,

4

00:00:12,980  -->  00:00:16,080
understand, and generate text.

5

00:00:16,170  -->  00:00:22,325
This architecture was first presented in the Attention is All You Need paper,

6

00:00:22,325  -->  00:00:28,190
and was originally designed to translate text from one language to the other.

7

00:00:28,190  -->  00:00:34,310
But in this course, we won't implement the architecture presented in the original paper.

8

00:00:34,310  -->  00:00:40,695
Instead, we will cover a different architecture used by models like GPT,

9

00:00:40,695  -->  00:00:43,915
LLaMA, and other similar models.

10

00:00:43,915  -->  00:00:47,420
In addition to being used by these popular models,

11

00:00:47,420  -->  00:00:50,340
it will be easier to understand and implement,

12

00:00:50,340  -->  00:00:52,580
but closer to the end of this lesson,

13

00:00:52,580  -->  00:00:57,960
we will compare it to the original architecture and learn how does it differ.

14

00:00:57,960  -->  00:01:04,705
Now, let's start with a 10,000-feet overview of how transformer model works.

15

00:01:04,705  -->  00:01:07,030
When we have an input prompt,

16

00:01:07,030  -->  00:01:09,750
we first split it into separate tokens.

17

00:01:09,750  -->  00:01:12,910
We convert each token into token ID

18

00:01:12,910  -->  00:01:17,550
and then convert each token ID into its own embedding vector.

19

00:01:17,550  -->  00:01:22,070
I made here a few details on how the wording embeddings are processed,

20

00:01:22,070  -->  00:01:27,280
but for now, I want to focus just on the core aspects of how it works.

21

00:01:27,280  -->  00:01:33,550
One thing to note here is that the same token ID will produce the same embedding vector.

22

00:01:33,550  -->  00:01:39,670
This is just a simple mapping from a token ID to a corresponding embedding vector.

23

00:01:39,670  -->  00:01:42,450
Once we have the input wording beddings,

24

00:01:42,450  -->  00:01:48,210
we pass them to the attention block that updates embeddings to refine their meaning.

25

00:01:48,210  -->  00:01:51,870
Here is an example of why it might be useful.

26

00:01:51,870  -->  00:01:54,710
Let's consider two sentences.

27

00:01:54,710  -->  00:01:59,690
One is her favorite fruit is a date and the other one,

28

00:01:59,690  -->  00:02:02,475
Kate and Josh went on a date.

29

00:02:02,475  -->  00:02:05,780
Both of these sentences have word date,

30

00:02:05,780  -->  00:02:09,230
but it has different meaning in both sentences.

31

00:02:09,230  -->  00:02:11,960
In the first sentence, it is the name of a fruit,

32

00:02:11,960  -->  00:02:13,620
and in the second sentence,

33

00:02:13,620  -->  00:02:16,040
it is an appointment to meet someone.

34

00:02:16,040  -->  00:02:19,820
However, after we convert input to embedding vectors,

35

00:02:19,820  -->  00:02:25,240
we will end up with the same embedding vectors for the word date in both sentences.

36

00:02:25,240  -->  00:02:30,340
To fix this, the attention mechanism in transformer architecture will update

37

00:02:30,340  -->  00:02:33,240
the embedding vectors based on the context

38

00:02:33,240  -->  00:02:36,560
of the other embedding vectors forming the input.

39

00:02:36,560  -->  00:02:40,660
In the first sentence, it might use the word fruit to update the meaning of

40

00:02:40,660  -->  00:02:46,140
the vector for word date to represent that this is a fruit that you can eat.

41

00:02:46,140  -->  00:02:50,680
In the second sentence, it can use some other words to update the meaning of

42

00:02:50,680  -->  00:02:55,680
the embedding vector to represent that this is an appointment to meet.

43

00:02:55,680  -->  00:03:00,520
The process of interaction between embedding vectors is called attention,

44

00:03:00,520  -->  00:03:05,560
and each embedding vector is influenced by other embedding vectors in the text,

45

00:03:05,560  -->  00:03:08,820
depending on the context of the text.

46

00:03:08,820  -->  00:03:12,325
To update the values of embedding vectors,

47

00:03:12,325  -->  00:03:15,660
the attention block calculates the attention scores.

48

00:03:15,660  -->  00:03:19,500
We will cover how these values are calculated in more details,

49

00:03:19,500  -->  00:03:23,860
but it shows the attention scores between each pair of input tokens.

50

00:03:23,860  -->  00:03:26,660
These attention scores are then used to

51

00:03:26,660  -->  00:03:30,080
update embedding vectors for all tokens in the input.

52

00:03:30,080  -->  00:03:32,880
Once we run the input through the attention block,

53

00:03:32,880  -->  00:03:36,140
we get updated embedding vectors that should better

54

00:03:36,140  -->  00:03:40,240
represent the meaning of each token in the context of the input.

55

00:03:40,240  -->  00:03:43,060
Once we run the input through the attention block,

56

00:03:43,060  -->  00:03:46,200
we get updated embedding vectors that should better

57

00:03:46,200  -->  00:03:51,115
represent the meaning of each token in the context of the input.

58

00:03:51,115  -->  00:03:56,340
The attention mechanism is the most important part of the transformer architecture.

59

00:03:56,340  -->  00:03:58,910
After we get an output from an attention block,

60

00:03:58,910  -->  00:04:01,960
we pass it to the feed-forward network.

61

00:04:01,960  -->  00:04:04,960
This combination of the attention block and

62

00:04:04,960  -->  00:04:08,060
the feed-forward network form a transformer block,

63

00:04:08,060  -->  00:04:12,260
or how it is also called a layer of a transformer model.

64

00:04:12,260  -->  00:04:15,280
We then chain multiple layers together when

65

00:04:15,280  -->  00:04:19,000
output from one layer becomes the input into another layer.

66

00:04:19,000  -->  00:04:22,060
Then we repeat the process again and again until we get

67

00:04:22,060  -->  00:04:25,300
the output from the last layer, and then at the end,

68

00:04:25,300  -->  00:04:28,720
we get the probability distribution for what our model

69

00:04:28,720  -->  00:04:33,560
considers to be the next token you should generate given its input.

70

00:04:34,020  -->  00:04:40,560
Here it gives 68% probability for a token with a particular token ID.

71

00:04:40,560  -->  00:04:44,720
If you're not familiar with the softmax function, don't worry.

72

00:04:44,720  -->  00:04:50,560
We will cover how it works and what is the rationale behind it just a bit later.

73

00:04:50,560  -->  00:04:55,280
Transformers have a few benefits comparing to other models.

74

00:04:55,280  -->  00:04:58,720
First, transformers can process input in parallel.

75

00:04:58,720  -->  00:05:02,605
They can process the whole input prompt all at once.

76

00:05:02,605  -->  00:05:06,020
They can access information in longer text much more

77

00:05:06,020  -->  00:05:12,040
efficiently and they're much easier to train comparing to RNN models.

78

00:05:12,040  -->  00:05:17,860
Most importantly, they perform amazingly well on real-world tasks.

79

00:05:17,860  -->  00:05:24,000
One other thing that we need to cover regarding LLMs is the concept of a context window.

80

00:05:24,000  -->  00:05:27,280
Context window is the maximum number of tokens,

81

00:05:27,280  -->  00:05:29,600
a model can handle at once,

82

00:05:29,600  -->  00:05:36,120
and it includes an input prompt and the output that model has generated so far.

83

00:05:36,120  -->  00:05:40,780
If we have a text that is longer than the context window of our model,

84

00:05:40,780  -->  00:05:45,500
then our model won't be able to see all of it at once.

85

00:05:45,620  -->  00:05:50,360
The size of the context window depends on the model we use.

86

00:05:50,360  -->  00:05:51,920
In a smaller model,

87

00:05:51,920  -->  00:05:54,640
it is limited to just 2,000 tokens,

88

00:05:54,640  -->  00:05:57,670
like in the first version of GPT3.

89

00:05:57,670  -->  00:06:01,340
But there are models with the context window that is greater than

90

00:06:01,340  -->  00:06:05,880
1.5 million tokens like recent Gemini models.

91

00:06:05,880  -->  00:06:10,680
Keep in mind that one word is not equal to one token since

92

00:06:10,680  -->  00:06:15,430
tokenizers can split a single word into several tokens.

93

00:06:15,430  -->  00:06:17,920
For example, in GPT model,

94

00:06:17,920  -->  00:06:23,220
on average, it takes four tokens to represent three words.
